How the Financial Rules of Football Will Affect the Transfer of Neymar to Paris
The rules restricting the financing of European football clubs will in no way disrupt Neymar’s record transfer from Spain to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 state that PSG will have to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid EUR 222 million to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar would demand a salary of several tens of millions a year.
There are several financial conditions following Neymar's transfer to France.
Since the PSG team is funded by a rich Cathar family that has become rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already star football family.
Clubs can spend huge amounts on buying players, but on the other hand, they must demonstrate legal sources of income, allowing them to cover the overheads of football-related business activities.
FFP introduced Michel Platini after the appointment of Director of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that were in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements were ultimately deceiving and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, FFP’s rules redirected its attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spent a lot of money on players y to build a global brand - was suddenly not so advantageous.
In the current three-year trial period ending in 2018, clubs may report losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Cheferin, is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
"The FFP rules still apply and we are committed to strengthening them in the future," he said last week for Associated Press Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with FFP rules.
Although the PSG has paid Neymara a one-off payment, it may, for accounting purposes, spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down to EUR 44,4 million each year for a period of five years.
The first wave of the highest sanctions FFP hit in 2014 PSG together with Manchester City, owned by Abu Dhabi Group.
PSG is fined EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to EUR 20 million - and a command to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is careful about teams that can attempt to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Catharic company sponsors the PSG once the financing exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority of the PSG team was too high.
According to some reports, part of Neymar's PSG revenue could be paid from the MS Football Commission 2022 in Qatar.
However, the PSG and the representatives of the MS 2022 in Qatar denied that Neymat should become an ambassador to the World Cup in football and that such a maneuver would easily be revealed by UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on the PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to Tuesday's informed UEFA, there was no investigation into Neymara's transfer to the PSG.
The source of this report wished to remain anonymous as it was not entitled to comment on the situation with the PSG, said The Associated Press.
The latest published financial statements show that the PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of EUR 10 million and a turnover of EUR 542.4 million.
The accounts for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and selling jerseys.
The club expects an increase in turnover of up to 30 percent from signing the contract.
The Spanish League’s leaders, evidently concerned about the departure of one of the greatest stars, sought to thwart Neymar’s departure, arguing that PSG would violate FFP rules.
“This is a clear case of “financial doping” the club and the state,” said the President of la Liga Javier Teba for the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the ownership of PSG by the Cathar Syndicate.
Arsenal Arsene Wenger, whose club owns an American sports tycoon, shares the same position of the La League on club financing.
"It is the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the football world over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
