From September onwards, patients will gain access to “transformative” treatment to prevent HIV based on the Supreme Court’s decision to fund NHS.
The National Health Service of England (NSH) reported that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period through medical services.
NSH agreed to finance the trial period after the Court of Appeal supported the Supreme Court ruling of last year, stating that NHS had funds to pay for PrEP despite the statement that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by NHS England by Director General Simon Stevens as a ‘significant intervention’, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a ‘decisive moment’.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 will be fully implemented across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV between patients at risk.
Pre-sex administration of PrEP means that there are enough specific medicines in the patient’ s body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transsexual people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics shall identify eligible participants who will sign approval to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexuals and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program comes to taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to distribute drugs this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years' effort to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Managing Director of NAT (National Aids Trust) said: ‘We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of changing the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH has been offering patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to coax a partner, leading to improvements in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, Managing Director of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: ‘Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests throughout the country; we must ensure that every patient is kept available.
We now have a PrEP trial drug at our disposal, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Secretary of Health Sharon Hodgson said: ‘The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
