“Do you remember how I taught you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?” he recalls the interview.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old, and that's not right."
"It was out of the question that I would not take her with me," Ferrell later said.
“Today’s events are the culmination... that has occurred in the past.
She must have known and seen it with her own eyes and grew up in it.
It needed to develop not only in activism and organization, but also to recognize the difference between the different layers of experience with black people and what we need to do to free ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own, she is no different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I were to protect her from this experience, I would only harm her."
Upon arriving in Ferguson, the first stop on South Florissant Road was opposite the police department, which became the base of activists who expected the words of Officer Darren Wilson about his possible involvement in the incident.
This is where Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing for the rest of the meal.
Together, they prepared food in bags and helped distribute it to Protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new type of activism was slowly born.
"My activism turned upside down after August 9," Ferrell said, adding that in her studies at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, Ferrell became acquainted with the later documentary director, Sabaah Folayan, during the evening demonstration.
Folayan said that he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "only document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell, however, wondered: “Do you work on a document or are you trying to find a story that could be used? ”
Such a type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often white people, who wanted to earn money from pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an unquenchable conversation: “We heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that. ”
Folayan has already established cooperation with co-director Damon Davis, who is a respected local artist who deals with the subject of prisoners on death row.
Ferrell, along with six other local residents who were watching the "Whose Streets" team in the years following Brown's murder, also integrated his participation in the project.
"In this document nobody speaks for us, but it is our testimony," Davis said.
"This was important to me - how these people will be represented - because in the same way I will be represented."
While the aim of the document was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an effort to show that the movement "is not about the savior leader, but about the community's rapprochement," said Folayan - it turned out to be the most open-minded of film participation.
The documentary “Whose Streets?” describes the very personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said, smiling at the thought of the first moment when she saw the final version of the document.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and to humanize the blacks, I had to open up."
In addition, Ferrell’s story highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in the wider aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created in response to the murder of youngster Trayvon Martin in 2012 on social media campaign under #BlackLivesMatter - call themselves weirdos.
"Black eccentric women in leading positions are ultimately behind the preservation of the movement," Ferrell said, "because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the weight of these events."
Folayan agrees with this statement and adds that “the move is actually supported by black women and a lot of eccentric black women.”
However, she insists that "this is not a mere acquittal" and Ferrell is not the main hero of the documentary because of her opinions.
"It was she who was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
“that she was the one who found herself in the front lines is no accident, because life on these intersections in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the surge of energy in front of the screen."
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, TV station cameras have cleared out their positions, but severe racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year probation for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
She described the social political atmosphere in the area she calls home as a "disorder."
Still, she hasn't stopped trying, which she's committed to since she hit the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
All we have to lose are our chains."
