In the center of one of the rooms in the New York Fridman Gallery there are several faces of different skin shades - white, black and brown - hanging from the ceiling on the wires. Each one of them seemed to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cable on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2nd, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, which combines her experience with technology, computer science and art, and Manning - a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence reduced Obama three days before leaving the post of President of the United States.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a razor-sharp, if not intellectual comment about DNA yield, as well as many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward Manning, spoke from her youth of being considered a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of 20 charges, including violations of six spy laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were held by prison employees, and only one black and white photograph of a lower quality, which Manning, visibly concerned, was leaked to the public, sitting in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, positive responses to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions were still coming out.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
