Under the statement of the artist on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in surname is printed with a heart) after the end of "self-involved factionism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By classifying 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope that people will get away with it, that our genome doesn't care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg. Her 2007 work on video is also available.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
