Facebook is planning a more thorough check of facts to limit the number of false messages
Facebook will send more potentially false articles to control third parties and display findings under original posts in an effort to combat the so-called "fake news", said the largest social network on Thursday.
The company writes in a statement on its website that it will start using up-to-date machine learning to detect possible hoaxes that will be sent to third parties to verify and potentially display survey results under original contributions.
Facebook was described as one of the main sources of false reports, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports affected the election of the President of the United States last year.
Political debates are being debated in Europe on the whole issue. French voters are flooded with an avalanche of false reports about the May presidential elections, and Germany plans to impose a fine on the social media network ahead of the September elections if it does not quickly remove angry contributions.
On Thursday, in his next statement in Germany, Facebook stated that it was planning to launch testing of a new fake news control function in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
"In addition to displaying reports verified by third parties, people ask for more content to be better informed and to be able to make the right decision about what they can share," said Sara Su, Product News Manager of Facebook.
She added that Facebook continued to test the "related articles" function and is also working on other changes to reduce the number of false messages.
Create a graphic novel: a story about A Castle in England
The small castle Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video of the Squeeze group, and Margaret Thatcher found her refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotland, however, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy place on the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, which inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County - a famous hobby in historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Look at the writing of a man who is 300 years after death fascinates me," Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived in the castle of Scotland from the Middle Ages to the Eduard period. Each story illustrates a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by archives: it is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of inspired documents of the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
“This is his thumbprint!
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those times you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, support from National Trust and Arts Council England and the possibility of staying in the castle almost as a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I extended my stay a little.")
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, going through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of hyenas on the wall and bottles that have been dumped in the ditch for centuries.
He walked around the property and examined the ruins of the old castle, talked to gamekeepers, gardeners and sometimes also artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he was "drinking whiskey and writing."
Scotney's confidential history is relatively unknown, since the National Trust organization gained access to documents only in 2006 after the death of Elizabeth Hussey's last heir.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as when “the aristocracy of many centuries throw their hands at the words, ‘Take it to the attic’.
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps of property: "You may think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch.
Stop it, people!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a stepping stone and sink deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising in 1381.
"I found a record of a riot in the castle from 1380, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually began in this area and I thought that rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected in the end."
Other stories are firmly linked to the history of the castle - such as The Priest, who tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell's family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about a smuggler from the 18th century named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes’ favorite family is Darrell’s: “I was intrigued by the male generation — men of that time were always in debt and were spending money on things they could not afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old wives - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake the heads of their heirs."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is searching for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week gig in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century, which was absorbed by nature.
But it's a strange place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I said to myself, 'Now get the hell back in real life'."
