The White House's prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the American manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records issued by the TIME Weekly.
The green white helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of the program of 17 July in the White House, which was a show of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials were inspecting a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was exhibited next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a forklift from Mississippi.
The military officer of the White House issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn in the framework of an "extraordinary" event, reports Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for the helicopter management.
"I wanted to make sure that you were aware of such a significant event," wrote HMX-1's commander in an e-mail to his supervisor, a representative of the Air Force Commander, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at around 7:00 on the occasion of the show, the beginning of which is scheduled for 15:00 and will remain in place until the entire place was completely cleared out, which was planned between 18:00 and 21:00.
The e-mail also said that if there is a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew for the return flight will be sent due to the Working Time Regulation.
The original crew remained in place that evening, along with the helicopter and with them, a unit of security personnel.
The records - received by the weekly TIME - did not show whether the second crew was finally sent.
Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this Regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was okay," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," replied the deputy commander.
This show "Made in America" was marked by the White House as an official event, so Hatch Act would not have applied to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his involvement in the event, the President advocated a health reform that went through the Senate and talked about trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of air transport vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
The presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was driving in the background during his first rally in the Melbourne campaign in Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the exhibition 'Made in America', which was presented by products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
The HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn area and rehearse any arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany at the beginning of July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to Made in America was part of the current crew training, said the state official.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew in the framework of “non-president support missions” for the next eleven hours.
The White House said that no more props were paid for from taxpayers' money.
Spokesperson Sikorsky said that the company was not in any way involved in negotiations on the issue of a helicopter at South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not retain budget records for presidential flights and the exact cost of the show is, according to the Navy, difficult to determine.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, the reimbursement of the DoD's expenditure for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit logs indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
"It is very misleading to report the costs of taxpayers on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenses," Walters said.
‘These estimates shall include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs which are included in the annual costs.’
According to the 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but include the cost of fuel, maintenance and contractual costs.
Back then, White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for show purposes.
"The idea of a fashion show this week is to introduce products produced in the USA," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide jobs to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of a helicopter and other military facilities, the production of which involves countless American citizens.
This fact is to be remembered."
It's not clear whether Trump was also looking at a helicopter during his rounds at South Lawn. The only thing to say is that he was behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House Trump approached a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
